rage their difference against language and the discursive. Similarly, questions about ontology have come to eclipse, and even eschew, those of epistemology.While this collection of essays is in kinship with this radical shake-up of how and what we study, the aim is to re-navigate what constitutes materiality. These efforts are encapsulated by a rewriting of the Derridean axiom, ‘there is no outside text’ as ‘there is no outside nature.’ What if nature has always been literate, numerate, social? And what happens to ‘the human’ if its exceptional identity and status is conceded quantum, non-local and ecological implication?"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCulturexPhilosophy. 0aMaterialism. 0aNaturalism. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aBarnwell, Ashley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiew, Florence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalziell, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Noela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinton, Peta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJamieson, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohncock, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirby, Vicki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiu, Xin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeimanis, Astrida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOxley, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311078140340uhttp